al Globe Books series surveys the distinctive but also shared rhetorical practices that characterize written requests for intercession, support, and patronage across many languages, cultures, and forms of interaction. Examples range from mundane requests to diplomatic negotiations, preserved in a variety of material media: potsherds, papyrus, paper, administrative handbooks, chronicles, and letter collections. Each contribution focuses on one textual sample or corpus of letters, providing new English translations as well as editions of the original texts in cases where no previous edition is available. Together, they represent the textual conventions and innovations of learned and vernacular epistolary traditions from many regions of North Africa and Eurasia, from the eighth to the fifteenth centuries CE.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aRhetoric and psychologyxEarly works to 1800vSources. 7aHISTORY / Medieval.2bisacsh  aepistolary traditions.  amedieval diplomacy.  amedieval social networks.1 aBossler, Beverly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandsma, Margreet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHagemann, Hannah-Lena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, Edmund, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristiansen, Birte, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiu, Jialong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLiuzzo Scorpo, Antonella, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMontel, Aurélien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPalombo, Cecilia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aScheerlinck, Eline, econtributor.4ctb4http